channel.title: Moons of the Solar System
channel.description: Demo site for tuts+ course on custom content types

item.title: The Moon
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded: Our own moon (Latin: Luna) is Earth's only natural satellite, and one of the largest moons in the solar system. It's thought that it was created when a large planet-sized body smashed into the Earth early in its formation.

item.title: Deimos
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded: Deimos is the smaller and outer of Mars's two moons. It's tiny with a mean radius of just 6.2km (compared to our moon's radius of 1737km).

item.title: Io
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded:
Io is Jupiter's largest moon, and the driest and most geologically active object in the solar system.
Its violent volcanic activity is generated by the forces created by Jupiter's vast gravitational pull on the moon, which causes the rock inside Io to turn to magma in the same way as high temperatures do to the rock deep within the Earth.

item.title: Europa
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded:
Europa is the smallest of Jupiter's Galilean satellites (i.e. those discovered by Galileo). But it's still the sixth largest moon in the solar system.
It has the smoothest surface of any known solid object in the Solar System, although that surface is covered in cracks and streaks. The surface is made of water ice, and it's thought that there could be a subsurface water ocean beneath it, prompting speculation that Europa may harbor extraterrestrial life.

item.title: Ganymede
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded:
Ganymede is Jupiter's largest moon and the third of the Galilean moons. It's the most massive moon in our solar system, with just over twice the mass of our moon.
It's large enough to have its own thin atmosphere, comprised mainly of O, O<sub>2</sub>, and possibly O<sub>3</sub> (ozone).

item.title: Callisto
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded: Callisto is the third largest moon in the solar system and the second largest of Jupiter's moons, after Ganymede. It's not close enough to Jupiter to have internal tides caused by Jupiter's gravitational pull, which means it doesn't have internal layers. More evidence for lack of geological activity inside Callisto is the fact that its surface is so heavily cratered: in fact, its surface is the oldest surface of any body in the solar system.

item.title: Welcome
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded:
This site accompanies a tuts+ course on custom content types with WordPress.
The site uses custom post types, taxonomies and fields to display resources about the moons of the solar system.

item.title: Mimas
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded: Mimas is the smallest body in the solar system which has enough gravity to be round in shape. It's only small though: its surface area is roughly the same as the land mass of Spain.

item.title: Enceladus
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded:
Enceladus is Saturn's sixth-largest moon. It's covered in fresh, clean ice: this makes it one of the brightest moons as the sun's light reflects off it.
It has tectonic activity with liquid water beneath the surface: in its southern hemisphere, the 'tiger stripes' are particularly active ridges where geological activity can be seen.

item.title: Titan
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded:
Titan is Saturn's largest moon, and the only moon in our solar system which we know has a proper atmosphere.
It's mainly made up of water ice and rock, and has lakes of liquid hydrocarbons on its surface, with liquid hydrocarbon rain. This liquid creates a climate in a similar way to how water does on Earth, but wouldn't be good to drink!

item.title: Oberon
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded:
Oberon is Uranus's outermost major moon. Unlike most moons in our solar system, Oberon (like Uranus's other moons) is named after a Shakespearian character rather than a greek god.
Oberon is the ninth most massive moon in our solar system and is made of ice and rock in roughly equal amounts, with plenty of impact craters on the surface.

item.title: Titania
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded: Titania is Uranus's largest moon, named after the queen of the fairies in Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream. Titania is made of equal amounts of ice and rock, probably with a rocky core and an icy mantle. It is thought that there may be a layer of liquid water at the boundary between the two. It is cratered but not as heavily as Uranus's outermost moon Oberon.

item.title: Triton
item.dc:creator: rachelmccollin
item.content:encoded:
Triton is Neptune's largest moon, and the only moon in our solar system with a retrograde orbit, which means that it orbits in the opposite direction to Neptune's rotation. Because of this it's believed that Triton wasn't formed with Neptune but instead that it's an object which was catered by Neptune's gravity - probably a dwarf planet from the Kuiper belt.
Triton has a surface of frozen nitrogen and a core of rock and metal. The fact that this is different from Neptune's composition provides more evidence for its having formed separately from its planet.
